const a = [
  {"id":1777,"text":"What is the cause of panacinar emphysema?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 90.\r\n\r\n(2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 675.","responses":[{"text":"Exposure to air pollutants","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Past severe infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excessive smoking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1846,"text":"A patient is taking some kind of RNA synthesis inhibitor for the treatment of a mycobacterium infection. They return back to the clinic extremely worried about recent events. They claim their urine, saliva, sweat, tears, and feces are all reddish-orange in color. What drug is the patient most likely to be taking?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 845","responses":[{"text":"Ethambutol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cycloserine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rifampin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoniazide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1912,"text":"Smoking is associated with which of the following subtypes of emphysema?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 675.","responses":[{"text":"Centriacinar","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal acinar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraseptal acinar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septal acinar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Panacinar","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2393,"text":"What is the most common type of bronchogenic carcinoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Siddiqui F, Vaqar S, Siddiqui AH. Lung cancer. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 20, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482357/\r\n\r\n2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 709.","responses":[{"text":"Small cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchoalveolar carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12512,"text":"Atopic asthma most commonly manifests at what age?","explanation":"**Atopic asthma** most commonly manifests during childhood. It often starts in **early childhood**, although it can develop at any age. Atopy refers to a **genetic predisposition to develop allergic diseases**, and individuals with a family history of allergies or atopic conditions are more likely to develop atopic asthma. The symptoms of atopic asthma are typically triggered by exposure to allergens such as pollen, dust mites, pet dander, or certain foods.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"Old age","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Childhood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Teenage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neonatal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adulthood","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12763,"text":"Nuclear medicine comes under which of the following fields?","explanation":"Nuclear medicine comes under the field of **radiology**. **Nuclear medicine** is a medical specialty that uses radioactive substances and imaging techniques to diagnose and treat various conditions. It involves the use of small amounts of radioactive materials, called radiotracers or radiopharmaceuticals, which are administered to patients either orally, intravenously, or by inhalation. These **radiotracers** emit gamma rays that are detected by special cameras, known as gamma cameras, or other imaging devices. The images produced by nuclear medicine techniques provide information about the functioning and structure of organs and tissues within the body.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory-II module, Community Medicine slides: Nuclear Medicine.","responses":[{"text":"Hematology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiology","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pediatrics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otolaryngology","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12764,"text":"Which of the following refers to the study of man and machinery in a workplace?","explanation":"**Ergonomics** is the study of how humans interact with their work environment, including the design of equipment, tasks, and workspaces to optimize safety, efficiency, and well-being. It focuses on creating a harmonious relationship between humans and machines in the workplace to enhance productivity and prevent injuries or discomfort associated with work-related activities.\r\n\r\nCommunity medicine, also known as preventive medicine or public health, is a field that focuses on the health of populations and communities.\r\n\r\nBioscience is a broad term that encompasses various scientific disciplines related to the study of living organisms. It includes fields such as biology, biochemistry, genetics, and biotechnology.\r\n\r\nBiotechnology refers to the use of biological systems, organisms, or their components to develop or create products and technologies for various applications.\r\n\r\nEnvironmental study, or environmental science, is an interdisciplinary field that examines the interactions between humans and the environment.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory-II slides, Community Medicine slides: Occupational Health.","responses":[{"text":"Bioscience","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ergonomics","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Biotechnology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Environmental study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Community medicine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16663,"text":"A 40-year-old female presents with exertional dyspnea, fatigue, and peripheral edema. Physical examination reveals an elevated jugular venous pressure and a loud pulmonary component of the second heart sound. An echocardiogram demonstrates dilated right ventricle. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Pulmonary hypertension** is characterized by increased pressure in the pulmonary arteries, leading to right ventricular overload and eventually right ventricular failure. This is consistent with the patient's symptoms of **exertional dyspnea, fatigue, and peripheral edema**, as well as the physical exam findings of **elevated jugular venous pressure** and a **loud pulmonary component of the second heart sound** (P2). The echocardiographic finding of a **dilated right ventricle** further supports this diagnosis, as it indicates right ventricular strain due to increased pulmonary artery pressures.","reference":"Dichter SL, Shubert GS. Argyll robertson pupil. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 3, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537179/","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary artery aneurysm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary hypertension","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary vasculitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16665,"text":"A 72-year-old female presents with bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy on the chest x-ray. She has been experiencing fatigue, dry cough, and shortness of breath. Laboratory tests show an elevated serum angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) level. A biopsy of the affected lymph node reveals non-caseating granulomas. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Sarcoidosis** is a systemic inflammatory disease characterized by the formation of **non-caseating granulomas** in multiple organs, most commonly the lungs and lymph nodes. The combination of bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, respiratory symptoms, elevated ACE levels, and the presence of non-caseating granulomas in the biopsy is highly indicative of sarcoidosis.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSilicosis is a pneumoconiosis caused by inhalation of silica dust, and it typically presents with nodular opacities on the chest X-ray, not necessarily with elevated ACE levels or the specific granulomas of sarcoidosis.\r\n\r\nLung cancer may present with a mass or nodules on chest imaging and can cause similar symptoms but would not typically present with bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy and non-caseating granulomas.\r\n\r\nHodgkin lymphoma can present with lymphadenopathy but is typically associated with different types of lymph node changes and symptoms, and it does not usually cause non-caseating granulomas.\r\n\r\nTuberculosis can cause granulomas, but they are typically caseating granulomas, not the non-caseating type seen in sarcoidosis.","reference":"Kahkouee S, Samadi K, Alai A, Abedini A, Rezaiian L. Serum ace level in sarcoidosis patients with typical and atypical hrct manifestation. Polish Journal of Radiology. Published September 23, 2016. Accessed July 5, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5036380/","responses":[{"text":"Lung cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hodgkin lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Silicosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16666,"text":"A 65-year-old male presents with fever, productive cough, and pleuritic chest pain. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds and dullness to percussion over the right lower lung field. Chest x-ray shows hilar lymphadenopathy and right-sided pleural effusion. Thoracentesis is performed, and the fluid analysis reveals raised white blood cell count with lymphocytosis. Microscopy reveals acid-fast bacilli. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Tuberculous pleural effusion** is associated with pulmonary tuberculosis and is characterized by the presence of pleural fluid that is typically lymphocyte predominant. The identification of acid-fast bacilli in the pleural fluid is a key diagnostic feature indicating tuberculosis as the underlying cause. The presence of hilar lymphadenopathy on chest x-ray is also consistent with this diagnosis.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nParapneumonic effusion is associated with bacterial pneumonia but would not typically show acid-fast bacilli.\r\n\r\nMalignant pleural effusion is associated with cancer and would typically show malignant cells in the pleural fluid.\r\n\r\nEmpyema is an infected pleural effusion but is more likely to show neutrophil predominance and positive bacterial cultures, not acid-fast bacilli.\r\n\r\nChylothorax is the accumulation of lymphatic fluid in the pleural space, typically with a milky appearance and is not associated with acid-fast bacilli.","reference":"Adigun R, Singh R. Tuberculosis. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 5, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441916/","responses":[{"text":"Parapneumonic effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Empyema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chylothorax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignant pleural effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculous pleural effusion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16679,"text":"Which type of hypersensitivity reaction causes antigen-trigger degranulation of sensitized mast cell residents in the nasal or bronchiolar mucosae?","explanation":"**Type I hypersensitivity** is also known as immediate hypersensitivity and is the mechanism behind **allergic reactions**, including common allergic responses such as hay fever, asthma, and anaphylaxis.\r\n\r\nIn type I hypersensitivity, exposure to a specific antigen (allergen) leads to the production of IgE antibodies, which sensitize mast cells and basophils. Upon re-exposure to the same antigen, these antibodies trigger the cells to degranulate, releasing mediators like histamine, which cause the typical symptoms of an allergic reaction, such as inflammation and bronchoconstriction.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nType II hypersensitivity involves antibody-mediated destruction of cells.\r\nType III hypersensitivity involves immune complex-mediated reactions.\r\nType IV hypersensitivity is a delayed-type, mediated by T cells rather than antibodies.","reference":"Abbas M, Moussa M, Akel H. Type i hypersensitivity reaction. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 5, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560561/","responses":[{"text":"Type IV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type I","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16680,"text":"Which of the following interleukin cause the recruitment of eosinophils at the site of inflammation?","explanation":"**Interleukin 5 (IL-5)** plays a crucial role in the growth, differentiation, recruitment, activation, and survival of **eosinophils**. It is particularly important in the context of allergic responses and asthma, where eosinophils are a key component of the inflammatory process.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nInterleukin 2 (IL-2) is mainly involved in the activation and proliferation of T lymphocytes.\r\nInterleukin 4 (IL-4) is important in the differentiation of naive T cells into Th2 cells and also plays a role in stimulating IgE production by B cells.\r\nInterleukin 3 (IL-3) supports the growth and differentiation of bone marrow stem cells but is less specific to eosinophils compared to IL-5.\r\nInterleukin 1 (IL-1) has a broad role in inflammation and acts as a fever mediator and an activator of lymphocytes.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 680.","responses":[{"text":"Interleukin 5","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin 3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16681,"text":"A 64-year-old man with 35 pack-year smoking history presents with shortness of breath. On physical examination, he is a thin, cyanotic man in moderate respiratory distress. His chest shows an increased anterior posterior diameter and breath sounds are faint with prolonged expiration. Which parameter is most likely to be found on the pulmonary function test?","explanation":"The clinical presentation described for this patient with a significant smoking history, shortness of breath, physical signs of cyanosis, increased anterior-posterior diameter of the chest, and faint breath sounds with prolonged expiration is suggestive of **chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)**. In COPD, particularly emphysema, the pulmonary function test (PFT) typically shows a **decreased FEV1 (forced expiratory volume in 1 second) and FVC (forced vital capacity) ratio**.\r\n\r\nIn COPD:\r\n\r\nFEV1 is often significantly reduced due to airway obstruction.\r\nFVC may be normal or reduced, but the reduction in FEV1 is typically more pronounced.\r\nThe FEV1/FVC ratio is usually less than 70%, which is diagnostic of airflow obstruction.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n\r\nIncreased forced vital capacity is not characteristic of COPD; FVC is usually normal or decreased.\r\nDecreased total lung capacity is more indicative of restrictive lung diseases, not COPD.\r\nIncreased FEV1 and FVC ratio is not typical of COPD.\r\nA normal FEV1 and FVC ratio would not align with the signs of obstructive lung disease presented by the patient.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 674.","responses":[{"text":"Normal FEV1 and FVC ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased FEV1 and FVC ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased forced vital capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased total lung capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased FEV1 and FVC ratio","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16682,"text":"A 65-year-old man comes to the office due to shortness of breath and peripheral edema. His symptoms have progressed in the last few months and have begun to limit his daily activity. The patient has 35 pack per year of smoking history. Physical examination reveals decreased breathing sounds. Chest x-ray reveals hyperinflated lungs. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)** is a common respiratory condition, especially among long-term smokers, characterized by **persistent respiratory symptoms and airflow limitation** due to airway and/or alveolar abnormalities. The symptoms of progressive shortness of breath and the development of peripheral edema (which could indicate cor pulmonale, a complication of advanced COPD) are consistent with this diagnosis. **Hyperinflation** seen on the chest X-ray is also a typical finding in COPD, often due to emphysema, which is a form of COPD characterized by damage to the alveoli.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nBronchiectasis typically presents with a chronic productive cough.\r\nPulmonary hypertension may cause similar symptoms but is less likely in the absence of other supporting clinical findings.\r\nPulmonary embolism usually presents acutely with chest pain and/or shortness of breath.\r\nLung abscess is typically associated with fever and productive cough, often with purulent or bloody sputum.","reference":"Agarwal AK, Raja A, Brown BD. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 6, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559281/","responses":[{"text":"Chronic pulmonary obstructive disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiectasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16683,"text":"One morning, a dead body was reported in a bedroom. The body was  suspended with a running noose around its neck. Dribbling of saliva was observed from the corner of the mouth. What will be the findings in case of ante-mortem hanging?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 164.","responses":[{"text":"Post mortem lividity on both feet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ligature around the neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ligature around the thyroid cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ligature not circling completely around the neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dribbling of saliva","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16686,"text":"A person died in an earthquake. A heavy piece of concrete was found over his chest. No other external injuries were present over his body. What type of asphyxia will you declare?","explanation":"**Traumatic asphyxia** occurs due to a sudden and severe compression of the thorax, leading to a rapid increase in intrathoracic pressure. This can result from heavy weights pressing down on the chest, as described in the scenario with the concrete slab. This type of asphyxia is characterized by the inability to breathe due to the compression of the chest and lungs, preventing adequate respiratory movement and gas exchange.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nGarroting involves strangulation using a cord or wire.\r\nSuffocation typically refers to a lack of oxygen in the environment or blockage of the airways, not direct chest compression.\r\nAutoerotic hanging is accidental death by asphyxiation during a solitary sexual activity involving self-strangulation.\r\nLynching often involves death by hanging and is associated with extrajudicial mob killings.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 161.","responses":[{"text":"Lynching","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Traumatic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoerotic hanging","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Garroting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suffocation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16715,"text":"A dead body was found under a collapsed building. A heavy piece of concrete was found over the chest. No external injury was present over the body. What classic injury is feature of traumatic asphyxia?","explanation":"**Traumatic asphyxia**, also known as crush asphyxia, occurs when there is severe compression of the chest, leading to a sudden increase in intrathoracic pressure. This can cause the rupture or severe damage of blood vessels and can lead to the backing up of blood in the upper part of the body.\r\n\r\n**Flail chest** is a specific type of injury that occurs when a segment of the rib cage breaks due to trauma and becomes detached from the rest of the chest wall. It is characterized by paradoxical movement of the chest wall (moving inward during inhalation and outward during exhalation), severe pain, and difficulty breathing. In the context of a collapsed building, such an injury could occur due to the heavy pressure placed on the chest by a concrete slab, even without external injuries being apparent.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 176.","responses":[{"text":"Fracture of upper limb","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Head fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flail chest","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture of lower limb","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16716,"text":"What is needed by the doctor before performing an autopsy?","explanation":"Before performing an autopsy, particularly in cases of unnatural or suspicious deaths, a **police order** is often required. This is to ensure that the autopsy is legally sanctioned, especially in cases where the cause of death might have legal implications (such as in homicides, accidents, or unexplained deaths). The police order indicates that the autopsy is part of a legal investigation to determine the cause and manner of death.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 99.","responses":[{"text":"Police order","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of magistrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dead body chalan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Detailed history of illness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Permission from relatives","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16717,"text":"In pathological autopsy, the basic objective is to find which of the following?","explanation":"In a pathological autopsy, the basic objective is to determine the **cause of death**. A pathological autopsy, typically conducted in a medical setting, focuses on understanding the medical conditions and diseases that led to the individual's death. This involves a thorough examination of the body's organs and tissues to identify any disease processes or abnormalities that could explain the cause of death.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 98.","responses":[{"text":"Virus responsible for death","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Manner of death","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pathophysiology of disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Time of death","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cause of death","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16718,"text":"In the death of a factory worker due to chronic metal poisoning which of the following should be preserved by the doctor?","explanation":"**Chronic metal poisoning**, such as lead poisoning, often results in the accumulation of heavy metals in the bones. The bones can retain these metals for a long period, making them a crucial specimen for confirming chronic exposure.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 113.","responses":[{"text":"Any bone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach and contents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver piece","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brain tissue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16721,"text":"Which general preservative is used in a mortuary?","explanation":"**Formaldehyde** is widely used for the preservation of bodies due to its effectiveness in inhibiting decomposition. It works by cross-linking proteins, which helps to preserve tissue structure and prevent decay.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 156.","responses":[{"text":"Formalin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saturated saline solution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formaldehyde","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spirit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absolute alcohol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16722,"text":"A dead body arrives at the mortuary. The death is because of radiation in some laboratories. During postmortem what precaution would you not adopt?","explanation":"Autopsies on bodies exposed to radiation should be conducted in a **controlled environment** with appropriate ventilation, not in the open atmosphere. This is to prevent the potential spread of radioactive particles and to protect the health and safety of the personnel conducting the autopsy and others in the vicinity.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nUsing long-handled instruments helps maintain a safer distance from any potential radioactive contamination.\r\nFreezing the body for 12 hours prior to autopsy can reduce the risk of aerosolization of radioactive particles.\r\nUsing proper doubled gloves and other personal protective equipment (PPE) is essential for safety.\r\nNot performing autopsy if you have any cuts on your hands is a standard precaution to avoid personal exposure to potentially hazardous materials, including radiation.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 125.","responses":[{"text":"Don't perform autopsy if you have any cuts in hands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Used long handled instruments","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perform autopsy in open atmosphere","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Freeze body for 12 hours prior to autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Use proper doubled gloves","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16765,"text":"A 4-year-old child is brought to the emergency room with complaints of cough for 2 days and shortness of breath since evening. He had similar complaints in the past also. Father has a history of atopic allergy. On examination, his respiratory rate is 54/min, and on auscultation, bilateral wheeze is present. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Asthma in children** often presents with **recurrent episodes of cough, wheezing, and difficulty breathing**. These symptoms can be triggered or worsened by various factors, including respiratory infections, allergens, and irritants. The family history of atopic allergy and the recurrent nature of the symptoms strongly suggest asthma.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPneumonia typically presents with fever, cough, and focal findings on auscultation, such as crackles or decreased breath sounds in a particular area of the lung.\r\nTracheitis often presents with a barking cough, stridor, and signs of upper respiratory tract infection.\r\nCroup is characterized by a barking cough, stridor, and hoarseness, usually in younger children (ages 6 months to 3 years).\r\nBronchiolitis is more common in infants and young children and is characterized by wheezing, coughing, and difficulty breathing, often following a few days of upper respiratory symptoms. It's usually caused by viral infections like Respiratory Syncytial Virus (RSV).","reference":"Lizzo JM, Cortes S. Pediatric asthma. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 9, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551631/","responses":[{"text":"Tracheitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiolitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Croup","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16767,"text":"Which of the following drugs used for the treatment of tuberculosis is bacteriostatic?","explanation":"**Ethambutol** is considered bacteriostatic. Ethambutol works by inhibiting the synthesis of the bacterial cell wall, thereby preventing the growth of the bacteria, but it does not kill the bacteria directly.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nStreptomycin, isoniazid, rifampin, and pyrazinamide are bactericidal drugs used in the treatment of tuberculosis. They work by directly killing the ***Mycobacterium tuberculosis*** bacteria. For example, isoniazid inhibits the synthesis of mycolic acid in the bacterial cell wall, leading to cell death, and rifampin inhibits bacterial RNA synthesis. Streptomycin and pyrazinamide also have mechanisms that result in the death of the tuberculosis bacteria. Pyrazinamide also has bacteriostatic activity but is primarily bacteriocidal against actively dividing organisms.","reference":"Lee N, Nguyen H. Ethambutol. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 9, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559050/","responses":[{"text":"Ethambutol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyrazinamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoniazid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rifampin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16768,"text":"Which of the following drugs used in first-line tuberculosis have a narrow spectrum?","explanation":"**Isoniazid** has a narrow spectrum and is specifically used as a first-line antitubercular medication. Isoniazid is highly specific for ***Mycobacterium tuberculosis*** and is one of the mainstays of tuberculosis (TB) treatment. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nGatifloxacin is a broad-spectrum antibiotic and is not typically a first-line drug for TB.\r\nCapreomycin is used as a second-line treatment for TB, particularly in cases of multidrug-resistant TB.\r\nRifabutin is a derivative of rifampin and is used more commonly in situations where rifampin cannot be used, such as in patients with HIV receiving certain antiretroviral therapies.\r\nEthionamide is also a second-line drug used for treating TB, particularly in cases of resistance to first-line drugs.","reference":"Melander RJ, Zurawski DV, Melander C. Narrow-spectrum antibacterial agents. MedChemComm. Published November 6, 2017. Accessed July 9, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5839511/","responses":[{"text":"Capreomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gatifloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rifabutin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoniazid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethionamide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16769,"text":"In the short course regimen of treatment of tuberculosis of 6 months, how many months are pyrazinamide and ethambutol used for?","explanation":"In the short course regimen for the treatment of tuberculosis, which is a total duration of 6 months, both **pyrazinamide and ethambutol are used for the initial two months**. This is part of the intensive phase of treatment. The regimen typically starts with four drugs: isoniazid, rifampin, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol for the first 2 months. After this intensive phase, the treatment continues with just isoniazid and rifampin for the remaining 4 months, which is known as the continuation phase. \r\n\r\nThis approach is designed to effectively reduce the bacterial load quickly and minimize the risk of developing drug-resistant strains of Mycobacterium tuberculosis.","reference":"Padda IS, Muralidhara Reddy K. Antitubercular medications. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 9, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557666/","responses":[{"text":"Throughout the course","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Initial two months","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Initial three months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Initial one month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lat 2 months","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16770,"text":"According to the World Health Organization guidelines, new (untreated) sputum smear-positive cases of pulmonary tuberculosis should be treated with which of the following regimen?","explanation":"According to the World Health Organization (WHO) guidelines, new (untreated) sputum smear-positive cases of pulmonary tuberculosis (TB) should be treated with a regimen that includes **isoniazid and rifampin for 6 months** with additional **pyrazinamide and ethambutol during the initial two months**.\r\n\r\nThis regimen is part of the standard short-course chemotherapy for TB and is designed to effectively treat TB while reducing the development of drug resistance. The treatment is divided into two phases:\r\n\r\nThe intensive phase: Isoniazid, rifampin, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol are given for the first 2 months.\r\nThe continuation phase: Isoniazid and rifampin are continued for the next 4 months.","reference":"Padda IS, Muralidhara Reddy K. Antitubercular medications. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 9, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557666/","responses":[{"text":"Isoniazid, ethambutol, rifampin, and pyrazinamide for 6 months along with pyridoxine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoniazid and rifampin for 6 months with additional pyrazinamide in the initial two months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoniazid, thioacetazone, and rifampin for 2 months followed by isoniazid and thioacetazone for 6 months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoniazid, rifampin, and pyrazinamide for 6 months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoniazid and rifampin for 6 months with additional pyrazinamide and ethambutol during the initial two months","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16772,"text":"Which of the following anti-asthmatic drug produces rapid and long-acting bronchodilation?","explanation":"**Salmeterol** is a **long-acting beta-2 adrenergic receptor agonist (LABA)** that is used to control and prevent symptoms (such as wheezing and shortness of breath) caused by asthma or ongoing lung disease (chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, which includes chronic bronchitis and emphysema). It works by relaxing the muscles around the airways in the lungs so that they open up and you can breathe more easily. While its onset is not as rapid as some short-acting beta-agonists (like albuterol), it still begins to work relatively quickly and its effects last for a long duration.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nBitolterol and metaproterenol are short-acting beta-agonists, providing quick relief but not long-lasting effects.\r\n\r\nAlbuterol is also a short-acting beta-agonist, widely used for quick relief of acute bronchospasm.\r\n\r\nPrednisolone is a corticosteroid used for its anti-inflammatory properties in the management of chronic asthma but does not provide immediate bronchodilation.","reference":"Adams BS, Nguyen H. Salmeterol. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557453/","responses":[{"text":"Salmeterol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metaproterenol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bitolterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albuterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prednisolone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16785,"text":"An air pollutant that produces as a result of incomplete combustion of fossil fuels or any other organic matter, and when inhaled, it mimics oxygen. It can bind to the hemoglobin in the blood and prevent it from carrying oxygen. Which air pollutant is this statement referring to?","explanation":"**Carbon monoxide** is a colorless, odorless gas produced by the incomplete combustion of fossil fuels or other organic matter. When inhaled, it binds to hemoglobin in the blood with an affinity much greater than oxygen, forming **carboxyhemoglobin**. This binding prevents hemoglobin from effectively carrying and releasing oxygen to the body's tissues, which can lead to hypoxic injury and is potentially fatal. This interference with the oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood is the primary mechanism by which carbon monoxide exerts its toxic effects.","reference":"Hanley ME, Patel PH. Carbon monoxide toxicity. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 10, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430740/","responses":[{"text":"Ozone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon monoxide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrogen oxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulfur dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16786,"text":"Acid rain refers to highly acidic precipitation. The normal pH of rain is slightly acidic (~5.6), due to the reaction of carbon dioxide with rainwater. The pH of acid rain drops below 5.6. It becomes 4.4-4.2. Which oxides contribute to acid rain?","explanation":"The oxides that primarily contribute to acid rain are **sulphur** and **nitrogen oxides**. These oxides are produced from various industrial processes, burning of fossil fuels, and vehicular emissions. When sulphur dioxide (SO₂) and nitrogen oxides (NOx) are released into the atmosphere, they react with water vapor, oxygen, and other chemicals to form sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄) and nitric acid (HNO₃), respectively. These acids then mix with cloud moisture and fall as acid rain, with a pH lower than the normal rainwater.","reference":"Likens GE. Ambio’s legacy on monitoring, impact, and management of acid rain. Ambio. Published February 2021. Accessed July 10, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7782629/","responses":[{"text":"Nitrogen and hydrocarbons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphur and hydrocarbons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrogen and carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphur and nitrogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphur and carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16787,"text":"Which of the following is the most appropriate asthma diagnosis?","explanation":"**Increase in FEV1 of 12% and 200 ml in an obstructive pattern on spirometry** following the administration of a bronchodilator is a key diagnostic criterion for **asthma**. Asthma is characterized by **reversible airway obstruction**, and an increase of 12% and 200 ml in FEV1 post-bronchodilator is considered significant and indicative of reversibility, which is a hallmark feature of asthma.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWhile wheezing on chest auscultation is common in asthma, wheezing can be present in other respiratory conditions as well.\r\n\r\nPost bronchodilator FEV1/FVC less than 70% on spirometry indicates persistent airway obstruction, which could be seen in chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) as well as asthma, but it does not confirm asthma on its own.\r\n\r\nWhile a family history and elevated IgE levels can be associated with asthma, they are not diagnostic of asthma by themselves.\r\n\r\nChest X-ray shows hyperinflation can be seen in asthma but is not a diagnostic criterion. Chest X-rays are often normal in asthma and are more useful to rule out other causes of respiratory symptoms.","reference":"Kirenga BJ, Schwartz JI, de Jong C, van der Molen T, Okot-Nwang M. Guidance on the diagnosis and management of asthma among adults in resource limited settings. African Health Sciences. Published December 2015. Accessed July 10, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4765426/","responses":[{"text":"Strong family history of asthma and raised serum IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post bronchodilator FEV1/FVC less than 70% on spirometry","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest X-ray shows hyperinflation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wheezing on chest auscultation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in FEV1 of 12% and 200ml after bronchodilators in an obstructive pattern on spirometry","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16788,"text":"In a patient suspected of community-acquired pneumonia who has mild symptoms. Which of the following tests is/are indicated?","explanation":"In the case of a patient with suspected community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) who presents with mild symptoms, often no initial diagnostic testing is indicated, particularly in outpatient settings. The decision to pursue diagnostic testing depends on the severity of the illness, the presence of comorbidities, and the likelihood of complications.\r\n\r\nFor mild cases of CAP, especially in otherwise healthy individuals, the treatment is typically **empirical**, based on clinical presentation. Extensive testing like CBC, blood culture, chest X-ray, or sputum culture is generally reserved for patients with more severe symptoms, those who are hospitalized, or those who have other health complications that may complicate the pneumonia or its treatment.","reference":"Fong IW. Issues in community-acquired pneumonia. Current Trends and Concerns in Infectious Diseases. Published March 7, 2020. Accessed July 10, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7120789/","responses":[{"text":"Sputum for culture and sensitivity (C/S)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CBC, X-ray, chest PA view, sputum C/S","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood culture (C/S)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16789,"text":"A patient diagnosed with pulmonary tuberculosis has never taken antitubercular drugs before. Which of the following regimens is most appropriate?","explanation":"The initial phase of the treatment for tuberculosis (TB), lasting 2 months, includes four drugs: **isoniazid, rifampicin, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol**. This is followed by a **continuation phase of 4 months** with two drugs: isoniazid and rifampicin. This regimen is effective for most patients with drug-susceptible TB.","reference":"Padda IS, Muralidhara Reddy K. Antitubercular medications. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 10, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557666/","responses":[{"text":"3 months of isoniazid, rifampicin, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol followed by 5 months of isoniazid, rifampicin, and ethambutol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 months of isoniazid, rifampicin, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol followed by 4 months of isoniazid and rifampicin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"6 months of isoniazid, rifampicin, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 months of isoniazid and rifampicin followed by 2 months of pyrazinamide and ethambutol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 months of isoniazid, rifampicin, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol followed by 2 months of isoniazid and rifampicin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16793,"text":"A 70-year-old male known smoker presents to the emergency room with complaints of fever and cough for 4 days and shortness of breath for 1 day. On examination, he is in respiratory distress with a blood pressure of 90/60, pulse of 110/min, temperature of 101F, and respiratory rate of 36/min. His chest x-ray shows consolidation on the right lower lobe with effusion. His calculated CURB-65 score is 4. Which of the following is the most appropriate step of management?","explanation":"The **CURB-65 score** is a clinical prediction rule used to determine the severity of community-acquired pneumonia and guide treatment location decisions. The score includes five factors: **confusion, urea level, respiratory rate, blood pressure, and age ≥65 years** (each factor scores one point). A CURB-65 score of 4 indicates **severe pneumonia** and a high risk of mortality.\r\n\r\nGiven the patient's high CURB-65 score (4), severe presenting symptoms (respiratory distress, hypotension, tachycardia, high fever), and evidence of consolidation with effusion on chest X-ray, the most appropriate management step is to **treat in HDU/ICU as severe pneumonia**.\r\n\r\nThis patient requires close monitoring and likely intravenous antibiotics, possibly supplemental oxygen or ventilatory support, and other supportive measures. The severity of his presentation and his high risk for complications necessitate inpatient treatment in a high-dependency unit (HDU) or intensive care unit (ICU).","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 583.","responses":[{"text":"Treat as ventilator associated pneumonia with MRSA coverage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treat outpatient with oral antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treat as hospital acquired pneumonia with injectable antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treat in HDU/ICU as severe pneumonia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Treat inpatient in ward with oral antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16797,"text":"A 32-year-old male who has a history of asthma comes to the emergency department with complaints of severe shortness of breath and productive cough for the last 1 week. Arterial blood gases (ABGs) are done showing pH 7.35, PO2=60 mm of Hg, PCO2=25mm of Hg, and HCO3=20. What will be the best interpretation of his arterial blood gases  (ABGs) report?","explanation":"The arterial blood gases (ABGs) report of this patient can be interpreted as follows:\r\n\r\npH: 7.35 (normal range: 7.35 - 7.45)\r\nPO2 (partial pressure of oxygen): 60 mmHg (Normal range: 80 - 100 mmHg)\r\nPCO2 (partial pressure of carbon dioxide): 25 mmHg (Normal range: 35 - 45 mmHg)\r\nHCO3 (bicarbonate): 20 (Normal range: 22 - 28 mEq/L)\r\n\r\nThe pH is at the lower end of the normal range, indicating that the patient is near the threshold of acidosis but currently within normal limits. The decreased PO2 indicates hypoxemia. The low PCO2 and slightly low HCO3 suggest a compensatory mechanism for hyperventilation, typically seen in respiratory alkalosis.\r\n\r\nGiven these values, particularly the low PO2, the best interpretation of this ABG report is **type I respiratory failure**. Type I respiratory failure, or hypoxemic respiratory failure, is characterized by a **low PO2 with normal or low PCO2**. It is often seen in conditions like severe asthma where oxygen exchange is compromised.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nType II respiratory failure, on the other hand, is characterized by both low PO2 and elevated PCO2, indicating both hypoxemia and hypercapnia. Respiratory alkalosis is indicated by a high pH and low PCO2. Respiratory acidosis typically involves an elevated PCO2 and decreased pH.","reference":"Mirabile VS, Shebl E, Sankari A, Burns B. Respiratory failure. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 11, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526127/","responses":[{"text":"Type II respiratory failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type I respiratory failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16799,"text":"A 50-year-old male chain smoker for the past 20 years presents to the emergency room with progressive shortness of breath, fever, and productive cough for 5 days. On examination, bilateral rhonchi are present. Arterial blood gas (ABGs) report shows a pH of 7.38, PO2=54 mm of Hg, PCO2=55 mm of Hg, and HCO3=26 mEq/L. What is the likely interpretation of his ABGs?","explanation":"The arterial blood gases (ABGs) report of this patient can be interpreted as follows:\r\n\r\n- pH: 7.38 (normal range: 7.35 - 7.45)\r\n- PO2 (partial pressure of oxygen): 54 mmHg (normal range: 80 - 100 mmHg)\r\n- PCO2 (partial pressure of carbon dioxide): 55 mmHg (normal range: 35 - 45 mmHg)\r\n- HCO3 (bicarbonate): 26 mEq/L (normal range: 22 - 28 mEq/L)\r\n\r\nThe patient's pH is near the lower limit of the normal range, suggesting he is close to acidosis. The low PO2 indicates hypoxemia, and the elevated PCO2 suggests hypercapnia. The HCO3 is within the normal range, possibly indicating a compensatory response to the raised PCO2. \r\n\r\nThis ABG profile is indicative of **type II respiratory failure**, also known as **hypercapnic respiratory failure**. Type II respiratory failure is characterized by both low PO2 and high PCO2. This condition is often seen in chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), a common consequence of long-term smoking.\r\n\r\nType I respiratory failure involves low PO2 with normal or low PCO2. Metabolic alkalosis and metabolic acidosis involve primary disturbances in HCO3 levels and corresponding changes in pH, which are not the primary issues in this scenario. The interpretation of COPD can be clinically correlated but not directly concluded from the ABG alone, although the patient's history and symptoms are suggestive of COPD.","reference":"Mirabile VS, Shebl E, Sankari A, Burns B. Respiratory failure. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 11, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526127/","responses":[{"text":"Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type I respiratory failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type II respiratory failure","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16808,"text":"A 63-year-old male patient with a history of diabetes and chronic obstructive lung disease presents to the emergency department with fever, productive cough, and shortness of breath for the past 3 days. On examination, he appears acutely ill with crackles on lung auscultation. A chest x-ray reveals a lobar consolidation in the right upper lobe. Sputum culture grows staphylococcus aureus. What will the gram stain show?","explanation":null,"reference":"Murdoch DR, Greenlees RL. Rapid identification of Staphylococcus aureus from BacT/ALERT blood culture bottles by direct Gram stain characteristics. Journal of Clinical Pathology. Published February 2004. Accessed July 11, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1770202/","responses":[{"text":"Gram negative cocci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram positive diplococci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram positive cocci in cluster","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram negative cocci in chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram positive bacilli","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16809,"text":"A 50-year male presents to the emergency department with high-grade fever, severe headache, myalgias, and non-productive cough. He recently returned from a vacation where he visited a popular hotel with an outdoor pool. On examination, his temperature is 40°C (104°F), and lung auscultation reveals scattered crackles. Laboratory test shows hyponatremia and elevated liver function tests. A chest x-ray demonstrates patchy infiltrates in bilateral lower lobes. Gram stains reveal gram-negative rods. Which organism is most likely involved?","explanation":null,"reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 170.","responses":[{"text":"Yersinia pestis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia col","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophila","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16811,"text":"A 72-year-old male with a history of chronic liver failure, diabetes mellitus, and hypertension is admitted to the intensive care unit (ICU) for septic shock secondary to a urinary tract infection. He is intubated upon admission and started on broad-spectrum antibiotics. On the third day of hospitalization, the patient develops a fever of 104.2°F (39.1°C) and increased purulent secretions. Chest x-ray reveals new infiltrates in the right upper lobe. Gram stain of sputum reveals gram-negative rods. Which of the following organism is the most likely cause of this patient's hospital-acquired pneumonia?","explanation":"***Pseudomonas aeruginosa*** is a common cause of hospital-acquired infections, particularly in patients in intensive care units, those who are intubated, or those with chronic illnesses. Its presence is often indicated by **gram-negative rods** in sputum cultures. This pathogen is known for its resistance to many antibiotics, making it a significant concern in hospital settings.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n*Neisseria meningitidis* is primarily associated with meningitis and septicemia, not typically a cause of pneumonia in hospitalized patients.\r\n\r\n*Moraxella catarrhalis* is more commonly associated with respiratory infections in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, not typically causing severe hospital-acquired pneumonia.\r\n\r\n*Mycoplasma pneumoniae* causes community-acquired pneumonia, typically not associated with hospital-acquired infections and presents with a different clinical picture.\r\n\r\n*Candida albicans* is a fungal pathogen that can cause opportunistic infections, including pneumonia.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 163.","responses":[{"text":"Moraxella catarrhalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycoplasma pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Candida albicans","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16812,"text":"A 4-year-old child presents with a history of low-grade fever and cough for the past 2 days. The cough is characteristically barking with hoarseness of voice. On examination, there is inspiratory stridor with no drooling or respiratory distress. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Croup**, also known as laryngotracheobronchitis, is a common respiratory condition in children characterized by inflammation of the larynx and trachea. The hallmark clinical features of croup include the **barking cough (often compared to the bark of a seal), hoarseness**, and **stridor**(a high-pitched breathing sound), especially on inspiration.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPharyngitis typically presents with sore throat and may be accompanied by fever, but it does not cause a barking cough or stridor.\r\n\r\nPertussis (whooping cough) causes severe coughing spells which can end in a \"whooping\" sound during inspiration, but it does not typically cause the barking cough or stridor seen in croup.\r\n\r\nEpiglottitis is a more severe condition that can cause respiratory distress, drooling, and difficulty swallowing.\r\n\r\nTonsillitis presents with sore throat, difficulty swallowing, and swollen tonsils, but not with the barking cough or stridor.","reference":"Sizar O, Carr B. Croup. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 11, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431070/","responses":[{"text":"Tonsillitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pertussis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epiglottitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharyngitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Croup","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16813,"text":"A 3-year-old healthy child suddenly develops a sore throat and fever. Within hours, the patient appears toxic, swallowing with difficulty and drooling, and labored breathing. The neck is hyperextended, and the child assumes the tripod position. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Acute epiglottitis** is the most likely diagnosis in this child who suddenly develops a sore throat, fever, appears toxic, has difficulty swallowing with drooling, labored breathing, hyperextended neck, and assumes the tripod position. This condition is a medical emergency characterized by inflammation and swelling of the epiglottis, leading to a rapid onset of airway obstruction. The classic presentation includes **high fever, sore throat, difficulty swallowing (dysphagia), drooling**, and **respiratory distress**. The tripod position (sitting upright, leaning forward with hands on knees) and neck hyperextension are postures that help open the airway.","reference":"Guerra AM, Waseem M. Epiglottitis. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 11, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430960/","responses":[{"text":"Acute epiglottitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diphtheria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Croup","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiolitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16814,"text":"A woman aged 25 has been diagnosed with pulmonary tuberculosis. She is also 8 months pregnant. When should she start her antitubercular therapy?","explanation":"Antitubercular therapy should be **started immediately** in a pregnant woman diagnosed with active tuberculosis, regardless of the stage of pregnancy. Delaying treatment poses a significant risk to both the mother and the fetus, as active tuberculosis can lead to serious complications. The benefits of treating active tuberculosis far outweigh the potential risks of medication side effects in this scenario.\r\n\r\nThe World Health Organization (WHO) recommends that pregnant women with tuberculosis should receive the same first-line antitubercular medications as other adults, starting as soon as TB is suspected and the diagnosis is confirmed.","reference":"(1) Zhou X, Fang G, Xie Y, Wei A, Huang F. Safety evaluation of antituberculosis drugs during pregnancy: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Frontiers in Surgery. Published 2022. Accessed July 11, 2023. https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fsurg.2022.871321\r\n\r\n(2) CDC | tb | fact sheets - tuberculosis and pregnancy. Published August 17, 2022. Accessed July 11, 2023. https://www.cdc.gov/tb/publications/factsheets/specpop/pregnancy.htm","responses":[{"text":"Delayed till after confinement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delayed till the end of first trimester","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Start immediately","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Delayed till the end of third trimester","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delayed till the end of second trimester","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16816,"text":"A 50-year-old male presents to the outpatient department with complaints of fever and cough for the last 5 days. On examination, his blood pressure is 120/90, pulse is 100/min, the temperature is 101F, respiratory rate is 30/min. Chest examination reveals bronchial breathing with dull percussion notes on the right lower lobes with increased vocal resonance. Which of the following investigation would confirm the diagnosis?","explanation":"The most direct investigation to confirm a diagnosis of pneumonia, which is suggested by the symptoms and clinical findings (fever, cough, bronchial breathing, dull percussion notes, and increased vocal resonance in the lower lobes), is a **chest X-ray (PA view)**. The chest X-ray can reveal areas of **consolidation** corresponding to the affected lobes of the lungs, which is consistent with pneumonia.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWhile a CT scan can provide more detailed images of the lung parenchyma, it is not the first-line investigation for suspected pneumonia and is typically reserved for complex cases or when complications are suspected.\r\n\r\nArterial blood gases (ABGs) can be helpful in assessing the severity of the pneumonia and the impact on respiratory function, but they do not confirm the diagnosis.\r\n\r\nSputum culture can identify the causative organism of the pneumonia and guide antibiotic therapy, but it does not confirm the presence of pneumonia itself.\r\n\r\nA complete blood count (CBC) may show an elevated white blood cell count indicating infection or inflammation","reference":"Pneumonia - diagnosis | nhlbi, nih. Published March 24, 2022. Accessed July 11, 2023. https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/pneumonia/diagnosis","responses":[{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT chest","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterial blood gases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sputum culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest X-ray (PA view)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16817,"text":"A 55-year-old female without known comorbidities presents to the outpatient department with complaints of fever and cough for 1 week. On examination, her blood pressure is 100/70, her pulse is 90/min, her respiratory rate is 20/min, and her temperature is 100F. On chest examination, her bronchial breathing in the left lower zone with decreased breath sound and increased vocal resonance. Her chest x-ray shows consolidation in the left lower lung. Which organism is responsible for her current illness?","explanation":"This patient's presentation of **fever, cough, and consolidation** in the left lower lung, along with bronchial breathing, decreased breath sounds, and increased vocal resonance in the same area, is suggestive of bacterial pneumonia. The most common organism responsible for community-acquired pneumonia in an otherwise healthy adult is ***Streptococcus pneumoniae*** (pneumococcus). The presentation is typical for a lobar pneumonia, which is often caused by *S. pneumoniae*.\r\nfeatures or affect different populations.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n*Staphylococcus aureus* can also cause pneumonia, but it is more commonly associated with post-viral infections or in individuals with a history of influenza. It might also present with a more severe clinical picture, including rapid progression and cavitation.\r\n\r\nTuberculosis typically presents with a more chronic course of symptoms including weight loss, night sweats, and hemoptysis, which are not described here.\r\n\r\nPneumonia caused by *Legionella pneumophila* often has a more acute onset and is associated with gastrointestinal symptoms and confusion, plus it often affects older individuals or those with comorbidities.\r\n\r\n*Chlamydia pneumoniae* typically causes a milder form of pneumonia and is more common in younger populations. It might also present with more systemic symptoms like pharyngitis, hoarseness, and ear pain.","reference":"Dion CF, Ashurst JV. Streptococcus pneumoniae. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 11, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470537/","responses":[{"text":"Mycobacterium tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophila","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlamydia pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16825,"text":"A 66-year-old man with 35 pack per year smoking history presents with shortness of breath. On physical examination, he is a thin, cyanotic man in moderate pulmonary distress. His chest shows an increased anterior-posterior diameter. Pulmonary function test reveals a markedly decreased FEV1 to FVC ratio. If a lung biopsy is performed on this patient, then which of the following features are most likely present on the microscope?","explanation":"This patient's long history of smoking, shortness of breath, cyanosis, increased anterior-posterior diameter of the chest, and a markedly decreased FEV1 to FVC ratio is highly suggestive of **emphysema**, a form of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). If a lung biopsy were performed, the microscopic features most likely to be seen would be **abnormally large alveoli separated by thin septa with centriacinar fibrosis**. Enlargement of air spaces occurs due to the destruction of alveolar walls, and this destruction typically begins in the centriacinar regions, especially in smokers.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nCharcot Leyden crystals are seen in conditions associated with eosinophils, such as asthma or parasitic infections.\r\n\r\nCurschmann spirals are also associated with asthma and represent inspissated mucus plugs that have been expectorated from the airways.\r\n\r\nGranulomatous inflammation is typically seen in conditions like tuberculosis or sarcoidosis, where granulomas form as a part of the immune response.\r\n\r\nSeptic infarcts occur when there is infarction due to infection, leading to necrosis, which is not a feature of COPD.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 677.","responses":[{"text":"Septic infarcts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Curschmann spirals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Charcot Leyden crystals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abnormally large alveoli are separated by thin septa with centriacinar fibrosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16831,"text":"Which of the following statement is correct regarding terbutaline?","explanation":"**Terbutaline** is a beta-2 adrenergic agonist that is primarily used as a bronchodilator to treat conditions like asthma. Like other beta-2 agonists, terbutaline binds to beta-2 receptors on the smooth muscles of the airways, leading to relaxation and bronchodilation. Prolonged use of beta-2 agonists can lead to **down-regulation** (a decrease in the number) of beta receptors, which can reduce the efficacy of the medication over time.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nTerbutaline is not typically administered transdermally. It is commonly administered via inhalation or oral routes for its bronchodilator effect.\r\n\r\nWhile terbutaline does produce smooth muscle relaxation, it is specific to bronchial smooth muscle rather than skeletal muscle.\r\n\r\nTerbutaline does not inhibit guanylyl cyclase. Guanylyl cyclase is an enzyme that catalyzes the conversion of GTP to cGMP, which is a different pathway from the beta-2 adrenergic receptor mechanism that terbutaline works on.\r\n\r\nTerbutaline is primarily metabolized by sulfotransferase enzymes, not by catechol-O-methyltransferase (COMT). COMT is involved in the metabolism of endogenous catecholamines like dopamine, epinephrine, and norepinephrine.","reference":"Slotkin TA, Seidler FJ. Terbutaline impairs the development of peripheral noradrenergic projections: implications for autism spectrum disorders and pharmacotherapy of preterm labor. Neurotoxicology and teratology. Published 2013. Accessed July 12, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3492522/","responses":[{"text":"Inhibiting the guanylyl cyclase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Produces skeletal muscle relaxation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolonged administration leads to down-regulation of receptors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Can be administered trans-dermal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolized by COMT","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16835,"text":"A 45-year-old male presents with a 2-week history of fever, cough, and pleuritic chest pain. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds over the right lower lung field. Chest X-ray shows a moderate-sized right-sided pleural effusion. Thoracentesis is performed, and the fluid is sent for analysis. Microscopic examination reveals numerous neutrophils, fibrin strands, and gram-positive cocci in a chain. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"An **empyema** is a collection of pus in the pleural space, typically due to an infection spreading from the lungs. The presence of numerous neutrophils and fibrin strands suggests an acute inflammatory response, while the identification of gram-positive cocci in chains is indicative of a bacterial infection, most commonly due to Streptococcus species.","reference":"Garvia V, Paul M. Empyema. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459237/","responses":[{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Empyema","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesothelioma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16837,"text":"A 6-month-old infant is brought to the emergency department with symptoms of respiratory distress. The child has had a runny nose and cough for the past few days, which has worsened. On examination, the infant has tachypnea, wheezing, and subcostal retractions. Chest x-ray shows hyperinflation and peri-bronchial thickening. Which of the following is the most likely etiologic agent?","explanation":"This infant with severe respiratory distress, hyperinflation, and peri-bronchial thickening on chest x-ray, is most likely has bronchiolitis caused by **respiratory syncytial virus (RSV)**. RSV is the most common cause of bronchiolitis and pneumonia among infants and children under 1 year of age.","reference":"(1) Jain H, Schweitzer JW, Justice NA. Respiratory syncytial virus infection. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed July 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459215/\r\n\r\n(2) Erickson EN, Bhakta RT, Mendez MD. Pediatric bronchiolitis. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519506/","responses":[{"text":"Rhinovirus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory syncytial virus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Influenza virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenovirus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Para-influenza virus type 3","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

